type="user">jms-0011</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-0011.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Chapter 3: the theory of universes">Chapter 3: the theory of universes</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Universes started their life in the <fr:link
href="sga-4.xml"
title="Théorie des topos et cohomologie étale des schémas (SGA 4)"
addr="sga-4"
type="local">Grothendieck school of algebraic geometry</fr:link> as a technical device to circumvent the annoyance that there cannot be a “set of all sets”; a universe is a set of enough sets, and whilst a universe cannot contain itself, it may nonetheless lie within an even bigger universe. Several important developments in the theory of universes from the 1970s onward by <fr:link
href="jeanb%C3%A9nabou.xml"
title="Jean Bénabou"
addr="jeanbénabou"
type="local">Bénabou</fr:link>, <fr:link
href="permartinl%C3%B6f.xml"
title="Per Martin-Löf"
addr="permartinlöf"
type="local">Martin-Löf</fr:link>, <fr:link
href="peterdybjer.xml"
title="Peter Dybjer"
addr="peterdybjer"
type="local">Dybjer</fr:link>, <fr:link
href="martinhofmann.xml"
title="Martin Hofmann"
addr="martinhofmann"
type="local">Hofmann</fr:link>, <fr:link
href="thomasstreicher.xml"
title="Thomas Streicher"
addr="thomasstreicher"
type="local">Streicher</fr:link>, <fr:link
href="steveawodey.xml"
title="Steve Awodey"
addr="steveawodey"
type="local">Awodey</fr:link>, and others have collided to deliver the present-day understanding of the centrality of universes in semantics: a model of type theory is just a special kind of universe in a special kind of category. This chapter provides expository background on the theory of universes, including a novel account of open and closed subuniverses to reflect the recollement theory of topoi from <fr:link
href="jms-0010.xml"
title="Chapter 2: the language of topoi"
addr="jms-0010"
type="local">Chapter 2</fr:link>. These open and closed subuniverses will play a critical role in the development of synthetic Tait computability in subsequent chapters.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
